### Current Behavior

the following code:
```javascript
const notifications = [<500 elements>];
await LocalNotifications.schedule({
   notifications,
});
```

triggers the following crash in the native code.

![Screenshot 2022-11-09 at 22 44 54](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2156263/201021269-3b74df76-66ec-4563-9690-2a51c36205d5.png)

### Expected Behavior

- Document this limitation.
- Behaviour:  either catch the native exception and pass it to the JS context so that try/catching would work,
or act the same way as iOS (which will silently ignore all notifications in excess)


the second behaviour can be simulated with the following code:

```javascript
const MAX_ANDROID_NOTIFICATIONS = 499; // 500 actually crashes
let notifications_to_schedule_ordered_by_date = [<more than 499 elements>];

if (Capacitor.getPlatform() === 'android') {
  notifications_to_schedule_ordered_by_date = notifications_to_schedule_ordered_by_date.filter(
    (n, index) => index < MAX_ANDROID_NOTIFICATIONS
  );
}

try {
  await LocalNotifications.schedule({
    notifications: notifications_to_schedule_ordered_by_date,
  });
} catch (error) {
  console.error(error); // the mentioned error will not be caught as it crashes on the native side.
}
```

